✅ 1️⃣ Is app/errors a Valid Place?

By default, Ruby on Rails does NOT generate an app/errors folder.

But Rails autoloads everything inside app/ (using Zeitwerk).

So if you create:

app/errors/invalid_amount_error.rb


It will work perfectly fine.

✅ 2️⃣ Correct Way to Define Custom Exception
# app/errors/invalid_amount_error.rb

class InvalidAmountError < StandardError
end


That’s completely correct.

🧠 Why Inherit from StandardError?

Because:

rescue => e


automatically rescues StandardError and its subclasses.

If you inherit from Exception, it will NOT behave normally in Rails error handling.

Always inherit from:

StandardError

✅ 3️⃣ Better Rails-Style Approach (Namespacing)

In real-world apps, we usually namespace errors.

Example:

# app/errors/payment/invalid_amount_error.rb

module Payment
  class InvalidAmountError < StandardError
  end
end


Now it becomes:

Payment::InvalidAmountError


This avoids name conflicts and keeps things clean.

✅ 4️⃣ How You Would Use It

Example in service:

def process_payment(amount)
  raise InvalidAmountError, "Amount must be positive" if amount <= 0
end


In controller:

rescue_from InvalidAmountError do |e|
  render json: { error: e.message }, status: :unprocessable_entity
end


Very clean separation of business error vs system error.

🧩 5️⃣ Do We Need To Configure Autoload?

Usually NO.

Rails (Zeitwerk) auto-loads everything inside app/.

Only if you create folder outside app/, like:

lib/errors/


Then you must add:

config.autoload_paths << Rails.root.join('lib')


inside config/application.rb

🔥 Interview-Ready Explanation

If interviewer asks:

Where should we define custom exceptions in Rails?

You say:

Rails does not provide a default errors folder, but we commonly create app/errors and define custom exceptions inheriting from StandardError. Since Rails autoloads everything inside app, no extra configuration is required.

Clean.
Architectural.
Professional.

⚡ Bonus: When Should You Create Custom Exception?

Create custom exception when:

Business rule violation

Domain-specific validation

External API failure abstraction

Want custom rescue handling

Example:

InsufficientBalanceError

PaymentGatewayTimeoutError

InvalidStateTransitionError

